narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: This is your standard second-semester analysis course, covering Lebesgue measure/integrals, Fourier analysis, and differential equations. It's fun, it's not hard, and it's essential for further mathematical study. Take it. Datta is a good lecturer and posts his (very, very good) notes online. The stylistic difference between Jones and Datta is almost comical.
If you're a serious about math, you're going to have to take it.
Math 305 is a solid course for the math major. It has a standard workload (for a math course) and is a significant improvement on math 301.

Absolutely take 305 if you're interested in the fundamentals of real analysis. Measure theory is shocking; the Fourier analysis and differential equations topics are quite beautiful. The course under Swarnendu was quite tough and demanding. He is a very clear lecturer, and a nice guy.
It's a continuation of Math 301, with some overlap. Pretty standard Analysis course: not easy to master but straightforward ideas. Swarnendu Datta is a good professor.
It's a second course in real analysis; if you like analysis, then take it of course. Homeworks were largely from the Professor's notes, and the tests were at a decent difficulty level.
